  "text": "CORRESPONDENCE 11 February 2025 By Andrea Cardini University of Modena and Reggio Emilia, Modena, Italy. “When departure and return are not possible on the same day ... the journey may begin at most the day before the activity starts and may end at most the day after.” This rule, from the Italian education ministry’s regulations for reimbursing travel expenses (see go.nature.com/4g4doia; in Italian), will be familiar to many researchers in Italy. Similar policies no doubt exist elsewhere — and are one of the reasons that academics continue to fly to meetings, despite knowing the harms (see Nature https://doi.org/n24k; 2024). Access options Access Nature and 54 other Nature Portfolio journals Get Nature+, our best-value online-access subscription $29.99 / 30 days cancel any time Subscribe to this journal Receive 51 print issues and online access $199.00 per year only $3.90 per issue Rent or buy this article Prices vary by article type from$1.95 to$39.95 Prices may be subject to local taxes which are calculated during checkout Additional access options: Log in Learn about institutional subscriptions Read our FAQs Contact customer support Nature 638, 321 (2025) doi: https://doi.org/10.1038/d41586-025-00433-4 Competing Interests The author declares no competing interests. Related Articles Academics say flying to meetings harms the climate — but they carry on Why a climate researcher pushed the limits of low-carbon travel — and his employer’s patience Four ways to build your network without attending a conference See more letters to the editor Subjects Latest on:",
